<raw><![CDATA[ * Global stocks rise on Barclay's results, US factory data * Euro rebounds but worries over Greece limit its gains * Oil gains over $2 a barrel on euro gains, Iran tensions * Bonds slip on stocks outlook, dim safe-haven appeal (Updates with U.S. markets, changes byline; datelinepreviously LONDON) By Herbert Lash NEW YORK, Feb 16 (Reuters) - Global stocks rose on Tuesday,lifted by Barclay's upbeat results and strong New York statefactory data, while the euro recouped some recent losses on theview markets had over-reacted to Greece's debt problems. The euro's gains were limited, as sentiment toward thesingle currency remained broadly negative because of doubtsthat Greece's debt problems will be resolved quickly. European ministers told Greece it may need to take furthersteps to bring its swollen debt under control and to calm"irrational" financial markets.For details see:[ID:nLDE61F0XT] The euro  was up 0.38 percent at $1.3649. Barclays Plc  beat forecasts with a near doublingof profits last year to 11.6 billion pounds ($18.20 billion),giving financial shares a boost on both sides of the Atlantic.[ID:nLDE61E0QU] Stocks got another boost after a gauge of manufacturing inFebruary in New York state easily beat forecasts as inventoriesjumped, the New York Federal Reserve said in a report.[ID:nN16239334] "The data we saw this morning is printing a pretty goodpicture for the first quarter," said John Canally, investmentstrategist at LPL Financial in Boston. However, some analysts were more skeptical afterscrutinizing the details of the release. "On the headline it was a really strong number but I thinkthe details overall are somewhat more bearish than the headlinewould suggest," said Anna Piretti, senior U.S. economist at BNPParibas in New York. "A lot of the improvement was driven by a correction ofinventories... It's a temporary factor." In early trade, the Dow Jones industrial average  wasup 67.27 points, or 0.67 percent, at 10,166.41. The Standard &Poor's 500 Index  was up 7.69 points, or 0.72 percent, at1,083.20. The Nasdaq Composite Index  was up 9.69points, or 0.44 percent, at 2,193.22. U.S. Treasuries fell as the stronger outlook for stocksdimmed the allure of safe-haven government bonds.[ID:nN16159849] The benchmark 10-year U.S. Treasury note  wasdown 3/32 in price to yield 3.71 percent. But in Europe risk aversion could be seen as the spread ofGreek government bond yields over core German Bunds widened.Increasingly tough European Union demands on Greece to tackleits budget deficit failed to win investors' confidence. EU finance ministers set a deadline of May 15 for Greece totake urgent measures to bring its budget deficit under controlin addition to a mid-March deadline for a review of itsprogress so far. [ID:nBRU010667] Oil jumped more than $2 per barrel to over $76, respondingto a euro clambering higher against the dollar and supported bygrowing tensions over sanctions against Iran. [ID:nSGE61F06Y] U.S. crude for March delivery  touched a session highof $76.50 per barrel, before easing back to $76.47, up $2.34for the session. The benchmark Brent contract for April delivery  wastrading up $2.64 per barrel at $75.15. The dollar extended gains versus the Japanese yen in theaftermath of the New York manufacturing data, hitting a sessionhigh of 92.90 yen  and was last up 0.1 percent at 90.10yen. The dollar was down against a basket of major currencies,with the U.S. Dollar Index  down 0.19 percent at 80.176. Gold prices rose more than 1 percent in Europe on Tuesdayas investors bought the metal to hedge against financial riskin the euro zone, and as the euro regained some lost groundversus the dollar. [ID:nLDE61F16H] Spot gold prices  rose $16.55 to $1,117.00 an ounce. (Reporting by Angela Moon, Vivianne Rodrigues, Emily Flitterand Burton Frierson in New York; Joanne Frearson, William Jamesin London; writing by Herbert Lash; Editing by Theodored'Afflisio)             ]]></raw>
